UN announces new targets in the fight against poverty
The United Nations begin immediately with the drafting of a number of new targets for the 12 years ago stated millennium development goals are to be replaced to fight poverty.
In the run-up to the UN Summit on Sustainable Development in Rio de Janeiro in the evening began, Australian diplomats played a key role in the push for "sustainable development goals" of the Millennium Goals are to replace expiring in 2015.
They were included in the final draft of the document, which will be adopted by world leaders, including Ms Gillard, at the summit.
UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon said in the evening at the summit, the time has come, "thinking about the national interest."
"I am pleased that the member states have agreed to take a process, with the universal, sustainable development goals are to be agreed," he said.
"These goals will build on our progress on the Millennium Development Goals and form an integral part of the framework for the development after 2015.
I will spare no effort to implement the mandate given to me by the member states to achieve our vision of sustainable development goals that build on the success of the Millennium Goals. "
